This division was suggested entirely by the metres and length of the poems, and not at all by their subject-matter , for the third group contains poems agreeing in subject and date with others in the first group (cf. eg, c. 99 with c. 48, c. 81 with c. 24, c. 93 with cc. 29 and 57). Within each group poems on the same or similar themes occasionally stand together (eg. cc. 2 and 3 , cc. 61 and 62, cc. 88-913 cc. 110 and 111), but more frequently are divided by one or more poems on another, and often a contrasted theme (cf. cc.5 and 7 , cc. 21 and 23 , cc. 62 and 64, cc. 69 and 713 cc. 70 and 72).

50. Another possibility suggests itself. The editor certainly must have disregarded what would have been the wishes of Catullus in publishing, or republishing, the poems against caesar, especially 11 none had yet been written in his favor. The edi· tor was doubtless one of the circle of literary friends of the poet at Rome, and so was, if not, like Catullus,a subject of sudden conversion, an anti-Caesarian.
